{
  "doc_id": "8549",
  "text": "The prevalence of H. pylori infection in this study was 74.4%, which is lower than that found in other Costa Rican studies [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . High rates of H. pylori infection are common in developing countries (80-90%; refs. [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and are usually associated with low socioeconomic status [CITATION_6] . We suggest that the socioeconomic status is one factor associated with the low prevalence of H. pylori infection in this study because the majority of the patients were of medium to high socioeconomic status (data not shown).",
